                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I was asked to write up a guide on how charmed pets wield weapons, and what kind of rules apply to them, so I took a bit of time and did just that.  Kinda long, but oh well!  Don't know where to really post it, so I'll post it here in the hopes that it's the right place:
<br />

<br />

<br />
Charmed Pet Weapons, or...  Getting the Most Out of Your Minion of Death
<br />
by Ayani Daishar of Povar
<br />

<br />

<br />
While a charmed pet is a wonderful thing to have, sometimes it becomes  important to raise the bar a bit... to get it to dish out death in a much  faster way than ever before.  That's where giving your pet weapons comes in.   Unfortunately, it's not as easy as simply giving your pet anything and having  it wield it, or even being able to wield it.  I'll go over a few pointers here to clear things up.
<br />

<br />

<br />
First off, all of us know that clerics and necromancers don't run around dual-wielding huge shiny swords, no matter how much they may want to.  But for our charmed pets, class isn't a problem.  A charmed cleric pet is more than happy to dual-wield what you give them, as is any other class of pet you can charm.  Basically, whatever class the charmed pet is has NO bearing on its ability to wield weapons.  The ability to equip weapons is a setting for each individual NPC, and seems to vary by zone more than anything else.  There will be many zones where you'll find that just about anything will wield weapons, and others, most notably Planes of Power, where very little will equip weapons you give them.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Well, that's great you say, but how do I tell if a pet is actually using that  weapon I handed it?  Great question, and there's a couple of easy ways to  tell.  First off, once you give a pet a weapon, you'll see it appear somewhere on their body.  Note that this doesn't always work, since not all NPC models actually show them wielding weapons (mostly older models of NPC's), so in that  case, you can Night's Dark Terror them to turn them into a NPC model that  clearly shows what they're wielding.  Another easy way to tell is to have your  "pet's hits" filter on and see what kind of damage they're doing.  If you give your pet a fine steel longsword and then see something along the lines of  "Charmed_Pet slashes a fuzzy rabbit for 363 points of damage!" then you know  the pet is wielding due to the slashing message.  Same goes for crushing/piercing/etc., just watch the messages, and you'll know that they're using whatever you give them.  In general though, mostly "humanoid" type NPC's  will dual wield.  This includes skeletons, the little alien guys in Luclin,  and other sorts of critters that are vaguely human shaped.  Another thing to  note, if you see a NPC wielding a weapon already (such as guards in Katta)  then it will also wield what you give them.
<br />

<br />

<br />
So now that the basics of what will use weapons is covered... it's probably time to move to the weapons themselves.  I've seen some people ask if a charmed pet will dual-wield two-handed weapons before.  Sadly, as neat as that  might be, the answer is no.  The reason for this though, is that two-handed weapons are "Primary" slot only.  Pets need weapons that are both primary and  secondary slot in order to equip them in their respective locations.  If you give a pet two weapons that are primary only, it'll just use one at a time and leave the other in its inventory.  Another thing is that charmed pets will equip weapons regardless of whatever class and race appears on the weapon's description.  As an example, you can give an ogre shadowknight pet two ranger-only weapons, and it'll wield both without any problems.  There are a few limitations though on what your pet will wield, and how it'll wield it.  First off, any and all nodrop items you give to a charmed pet are deleted.  No matter how neat that nodrop weapon you picked up might be on a pet, it won't be able to use it.  Second, you'll sometimes need to give your pet weapons in a specific order.  If you have a weapon that is primary-only that you want your pet to wield, make sure you give it to it first, as the first weapon you  give becomes the primary.  Same thing if you have a secondary-only weapon you want to use... make sure to give it to the pet after you give it something for its main-hand.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Some people have asked me what weapons to give a pet in order to maximize  performance.  I've seen some suggestions about weapons that proc damage or snares, but in my opinion, the absolute best weapon to give your pet is a Velium Swiftblade.  This weapon has a 35% item haste modifier (which stacks with all cast haste spells), and will make a HUGE impact in a pet's damage potential.  They're also fairly cheap to buy, should you lose yours in an accident.  But obviously, your pet wields two weapons, so that gives you another slot to fill.  My suggestion is to think about what kind of effects would be the most useful to you where you're charming and try and find a weapon that fits that.  Silken Whips of  Ensnaring, which proc a snare can be handy, though in many cases, you'll be rooting whatever your pet is killing anyway.  Gnoll Hide Lariets are also good  choices for lower level charmed pets, as the stun can reduce what damage your pet takes.  Personally, I've taken to using a Bloodguard Wand of Walking Dead, as it procs a small 5% damage absorbsion rune, which can be quite useful when dealing with NPC's that hit for massive amounts of damage.  It's also fairly cheap.  In addition, the mage-summoned weapons are good choices, as they proc for a respectable 150 damage, and fairly often.  Also, it should be noted that  no matter the delay and damage on a weapon, it won't affect a NPC in the slightest.  A pet with a 200 delay, 2 damage weapon will attack just as  quickly and hit for as much as one with a 15 delay, 100 damage weapon.  But  while weapon damage and delay is ignored by the pet, stats on items are not.  So if you give a pet a weapon or item with lots of + Magic Resistance on it, expect more charm breaks!
<br />

<br />

<br />
Well, that's about it really for weapons.  But there's still one more trick out there that will let you get the most from your charmed pet, and it's something that I've not seen a lot of people doing.  In addition to mage-summoned weapons, it's extremely helpful to get a bag of phantom plate and give it to your pet, as well as either a girdle or belt of magi'kot, as those have very nice stats for pets.  It's sometimes difficult to tell if your pet is using armor, as many NPC models don't display armor,  but pretty much all player race NPC's will show armor that they wield.  Phantom plate is a distinctive dark-reddish color, so if you give your human pet a phantom breastplate and their chest turns red, that's a sure sign they're using it.  Also, though not obvious, the summoned focus items are good to give to your pet too, as that fills in equipment slots that the armor doesn't and provides extra AC.  Also, if you can't get your hands on another kind of haste item, a summoned Muzzle of Mardu will work in a pinch, though it has signifigantly less item haste than the swiftblade.  All that AC from the summoned gear makes a huge impact in how well your pet takes a beating, and once you start experimenting with it, you'll find just how useful all that summoned stuff can be.  Make good friends with your local magicians!
<br />

<br />

<br />
I hope this guide helps clear up some things about charmed pets, and also helps to get you the most death and destruction out of your little charmed minion!</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
