                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Ayani wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Also, it should be noted that  no matter the delay and damage on a weapon, it won't affect a NPC in the slightest.  A pet with a 200 delay, 2 damage weapon will attack just as  quickly and hit for as much as one with a 15 delay, 100 damage weapon.  But  while weapon damage and delay is ignored by the pet, stats on items are not.  So if you give a pet a weapon or item with lots of + Magic Resistance on it, expect more charm breaks!
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
If I remember correctly, the delay correction was applied only to summoned and charmed pets not to NPCs in general.
<br />

<br />
Weapon damage works as follows:
<br />
If the damage delivered by the weapon exceeds the damage delivered by the NPC and/or Pet then the weapon damage will be used.  As everyone well knows this is rarely the case beyond about 4th level <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />  Thus the damage delivered by a weapon has no real bearing on anything.  However in the example above, the 100 damage weapon, in some Dire Charm cases, may well be higher than the mob is capable of delivering and thus the damage of the weapon will be used over the natural damage of the mob.
<br />

<br />
Weapon delay works as follows:
<br />
The delay on a weapon will affect the rate at which an NPC attacks, the rate at which a PET attacks is static regardless of weapons.
<br />

<br />
Thus, giving your charmie low delay weapons will not help you while the mob is your pet and will almost always hinder you when it is not.
<br />

<br />
Giving your charmie high delay weapons will not hinder you while the mob is your pet but it will help you when it is not.
<br />

<br />
The delay of the weapon overrides the natural striking delay of the mob.
<br />

<br />
So, when you hand your pet 2 fine steel daggers, the low delay on the weapons does not allow your "pet" to attack faster but when your charm breaks it will allow the NPC wandering your direction to dice and slice you quite quickly.  Now if the mobs natural delay beats that of a fine steel dagger then it will dice and slice you slower wielding daggers (this is rather rare however).
<br />

<br />
The long and short of it is that you will likely live longer on a bad charm break if you hand your pets weapons with as high a delay as you can find.  It will have no effect on the mob while it is your charmie and thus your DPS but it will definately save your bacon when the charm breaks.
<br />

<br />
Regards,</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Sage <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=370213" target="_blank" class="postlink">Zanithar TideBreaker</a> - Coercer
<br />
<a href="http://www.therelentless.com" target="_blank" class="postlink">The Relentless</a>, Cazic Thule
