                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think it's far more simple to not classify charmed NPC's by class when determining what will dual-wield because there's just no consistant rule on it.  Some casters can dual-wield, some can't.  Some warriors can dual-wield, some can't.  As I said before, it's just about the individual NPC more than its class.  Oh, and it's just personal experience that I've found that mostly humanoid-type NPC's tend to equip weapons.  As with everything though, it's a setting on the NPC itself, not based on its model, or class.  A cleric slime could dual-wield, while a human warrior NPC might not.  The best rule I can think of on this matter is that if you find one type of NPC in a zone that dual-wields, other NPC's of the same type or model usually do as well.  But again, it's all individual settings on NPC's more-so than any other overriding factor.  Anyway, this argument is pointless, as there's no hard and fast rule on this, and it is always best to test it out yourself rather than assume it wields just because it might be a warrior or a rogue NPC.
<br />

<br />
And as for giving your pet a girdle/belt of magi'kot... true, it's not as useful at higher levels where NPC's hit for 500+, but this guide was written for all levels of charming.  At level 30 for example, giving your pet an item with +500hps on it might indeed make a decent bit of difference in its ability to tank.
<br />

<br />
On the topic of weapon delay... I'll run some tests on that, but I seem to remember that damage and delay is a setting on the NPC itself, regardless of what it wields.  If not, then I'm sure there's some amusing exploitation regarding giving NPC's weighted axes to make them attack like slugs.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
